Here’s a simple sticky header example using **CSS** (for the sticky behavior) and a little **JavaScript** (to add a “scrolled” class for styling once you scroll).

### HTML
```html
<header id="siteHeader" class="site-header">
  <div class="inner">
    <strong class="logo">MySite</strong>
    <nav class="nav">
      <a href="#home">Home</a>
      <a href="#features">Features</a>
      <a href="#contact">Contact</a>
    </nav>
  </div>
</header>

<main class="content">
  <section style="height: 2000px; padding: 24px;">
    Scroll down to see the header style change.
  </section>
</main>
```

### CSS
```css
/* Basic layout */
body {
  margin: 0;
  font-family: system-ui, Arial, sans-serif;
}

.site-header {
  position: sticky;   /* makes it stick */
  top: 0;             /* stick to the top of the viewport */
  z-index: 1000;
  background: white;
  border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;
  transition: box-shadow 200ms ease, background 200ms ease;
}

.site-header .inner {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  padding: 14px 18px;
}

.nav a {
  margin-left: 14px;
  text-decoration: none;
  color: #222;
}

/* Style change after scrolling */
.site-header.scrolled {
  background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.95);
  box-shadow: 0 6px 18px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.12);
}
```

### JavaScript
```html
<script>
  const header = document.getElementById('siteHeader');

  function onScroll() {
    header.classList.toggle('scrolled', window.scrollY > 10);
  }

  window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true });
  onScroll(); // set initial state
</script>
```

This gives you a header that stays at the top (`position: sticky`) and visually changes (shadow/background) once the page is scrolled a bit.
